{
  "root_cause": "With SGLANG_USE_CUDA_IPC_TRANSPORT=1 but SGLANG_USE_IPC_POOL_HANDLE_CACHE left at its default (0), every multimodal feature tensor takes the non-pooled path in cuda_ipc_transport_utils.py: CudaIpcTensorTransportProxy.get_proxy_state calls storage._share_cuda_() on the MmItemMemoryPool slice's storage, producing a fresh per-tensor CUDA/HIP IPC handle that is sent to the receiver and opened with torch.UntypedStorage._new_shared_cuda(). The MmItemMemoryPool recycler thread (SGLANG_MM_ITEM_MEM_POOL_RECYCLE_INTERVAL_SEC) reclaims and reuses pool chunks across the 128 concurrent MMMU requests, so the device buffer backing an in-flight per-tensor IPC handle is freed/recycled on the sender before the receiver reconstructs the tensor from that handle. The receiver then opens a stale device pointer and HIP reports 'invalid device pointer', killing the TP1 scheduler (SIGQUIT).",
  "fix": "Set export SGLANG_USE_IPC_POOL_HANDLE_CACHE=1 in /app/launch_qwen3.5_27b_sglang.sh (keeping SGLANG_USE_CUDA_IPC_TRANSPORT=1). This switches _wrap_tensor_for_cuda_ipc in base_processor.py to attach the pool's single persistent _pool_ipc_handle plus pool_byte_offset to each proxy, and the receiver opens that handle once and caches it in _pool_storage_cache (cuda_ipc_transport_utils.py). The cached storage stays valid for the lifetime of the MmItemMemoryPool, so reconstruction always resolves a live device pointer regardless of chunk recycling, while the CUDA IPC multimodal transport remains enabled.",
  "evidence": "[2026-07-16 12:50:59 TP1] Failed to deserialize from CUDA IPC handle (HIP error: invalid device pointer ... hipErrorInvalidDevicePointer ...); File \"/sgl-workspace/sglang/python/sglang/srt/utils/cuda_ipc_transport_utils.py\", line 488, in reconstruct_on_target_device -> storage = torch.UntypedStorage._new_shared_cuda(...); torch.AcceleratorError: HIP error: invalid device pointer; [2026-07-16 12:50:59] SIGQUIT received. signum=None, frame=None. It usually means one child failed."
}
